The regular triangular tiling of the plane, whose symmetries are described by the affine symmetric group S̃ 3
The [affine symmetric groups](/Affine_symmetric_group) are a fascinating family of [mathematical structures](/Mathematical_structure) that provide a precise, rigorous language for describing the inherent symmetries found in both the boundless [number line](/Number_line) and the intricate, repeating patterns of the regular [triangular tiling](/Triangular_tiling) of the plane. These groups also extend their descriptive power to related higher-dimensional objects, hinting at a universal grammar of symmetry. Beyond this compelling geometric interpretation, the affine symmetric groups can be articulated in other equally precise ways: they can be conceived as specific collections of [permutations](/Permutation)—rearrangements—of the infinite set of integers (..., &#8722;2, &#8722;1, 0, 1, 2, ...), characterized by a particular, well-defined periodicity. Alternatively, they can be defined in purely algebraic terms as a [group](/Group_(mathematics)) that arises from a specific set of [generators and relations](/Generators_and_relations), a kind of mathematical blueprint. Their study is a cornerstone in the fields of [combinatorics](/Combinatorics), which explores the arrangements and combinations of objects, and [representation theory](/Representation_theory), which seeks to understand abstract algebraic structures by representing their elements as linear transformations of vector spaces.

Each affine symmetric group, in its infinite complexity, acts as an [extension](/Group_extension) of a finite [symmetric group](/Symmetric_group), meaning it incorporates and builds upon the properties of permutations within finite sets. This connection is not merely structural; it allows many crucial combinatorial properties that are well-understood in the finite symmetric groups to be extended and generalized to their affine counterparts. Concepts such as [permutation statistics](/Permutation_statistics), including [descents](/Permutation) (where an element is larger than the next) and [inversions](/Inversion_(discrete_mathematics)) (where a larger element precedes a smaller one), find analogous definitions and interpretations in the affine case. Crucially, just as in the finite domain, the natural combinatorial definitions for these extended statistics retain a profound and often elegant geometric interpretation, linking abstract algebraic properties back to visual patterns and spatial arrangements. ( [Full article...](/Affine_symmetric_group) )

