Image 3
Euclid's method for finding the greatest common divisor (GCD) of two starting lengths BA and DC, both defined to be multiples of a common "unit" length. The length DC being shorter, it is used to "measure" BA, but only once because the remainder EA is less than DC. EA now measures (twice) the shorter length DC, with remainder FC shorter than EA. Then FC measures (three times) length EA. Because there is no remainder, the process ends with FC being the GCD. On the right [Nicomachus](/Nicomachus)'s example with numbers 49 and 21 resulting in their GCD of 7 (derived from Heath 1908:300).

In [mathematics](/Mathematics), the [Euclidean algorithm](/Euclidean_algorithm), often simply referred to as Euclid's algorithm, stands as an enduring testament to ancient ingenuity: an extraordinarily efficient method for precisely computing the [greatest common divisor](/Greatest_common_divisor) (GCD) of any two given [integers](/Integers). The GCD, for the uninitiated, is simply the largest positive integer that divides both numbers without leaving a [remainder](/Remainder). This elegant procedure is, quite fittingly, named after the ancient Greek [mathematician](/Mathematician) [Euclid](/Euclid), who first meticulously described it in his monumental work, the Elements, around 300 BC.

It serves as a foundational example of an [algorithm]—a step-by-step procedure for solving a computational problem—and is remarkably one of the oldest algorithms still in widespread common use today, a testament to its timeless utility. Its applications are far-reaching: it can be employed to reduce [fractions](/Fraction_(mathematics)) to their [simplest form](/Irreducible_fraction), ensuring clarity and efficiency in calculations. More significantly, it forms an integral part of countless other number-theoretic and cryptographic computations, silently underpinning much of modern digital security and data integrity.

The very foundation of the Euclidean algorithm rests on a deceptively simple yet profound principle: the greatest common divisor of two numbers remains invariant if the larger number is replaced by its difference with the smaller number. Consider, for instance, the numbers 252 and 105. Their GCD is 21 (since 252 = 21 × 12 and 105 = 21 × 5). Applying the principle, the same number, 21, is also the GCD of 105 and the difference 252 − 105 = 147. Because each such replacement systematically reduces the larger of the two numbers, repeating this process generates successively smaller pairs of numbers. This iterative reduction continues until the two numbers in the pair become equal. At that precise juncture, the number they have converged upon is none other than the GCD of the original two numbers. Furthermore, by reversing the sequence of steps, or by utilizing the more advanced [extended Euclidean algorithm](/Extended_Euclidean_algorithm), this same GCD can be expressed as a [linear combination](/Linear_combination) of the two original numbers. This means it can be written as the sum of the two numbers, each multiplied by an [integer] (for example, 21 = 5 × 105 + (−2) × 252). The profound fact that the GCD can *always* be expressed in this manner is a fundamental result in number theory, universally known as [Bézout's identity](/Bézout's_identity). ( [Full article...](/Euclidean_algorithm) )

