Image 4
The weighing pans of this [balance scale](/Balance_scale) contain zero objects, divided into two equal groups.
In [mathematics](/Mathematics), the number [zero](/0_(number)) occupies a peculiar and often underestimated position, yet its [parity](/Parity_(mathematics))—the property of an [integer](/Integer) being either even or odd—is definitively and unequivocally even. This seemingly trivial fact can be effortlessly confirmed by adhering to the fundamental definition of an "even" number: an integer is even if it is a [multiple](/Multiple_(mathematics)) of [2](/2_(number)). In the case of zero, this is plainly true, as 0 can be expressed as 0 × 2.

Consequently, zero seamlessly integrates into and shares every characteristic that defines even numbers. For example, it is invariably neighbored on both its positive and negative sides by odd numbers (namely, -1 and 1). Furthermore, in any decimal integer, the parity of the entire number is identical to the parity of its last digit. Since 10, the base of our decimal system, is an even number, it naturally follows that 0, as a terminal digit, will impart an even parity. Moreover, if any number *y* is even, then *y* + *x* will consistently possess the same parity as *x*; indeed, 0 + *x* and *x* will always exhibit identical parities, reinforcing zero's even nature.

Zero's evenness is not merely a definitional quirk; it is a foundational necessity for the consistency of arithmetic's parity rules. For instance, the rule that "even − even = even" would crumble without 0 being even (e.g., 2 - 2 = 0). Beyond simple arithmetic, zero functions as the additive [identity element](/Identity_element) within the [group](/Group_(mathematics)) of even integers, serving as the neutral element in addition. It also crucially acts as the initial case from which all other even [natural numbers](/Natural_number) are [recursively defined](/Recursive_definition), forming the anchor of their generation. The practical implications of this recursive definition extend into various computational and theoretical domains, from the intricate structures of [graph theory](/Graph_theory) to the precise calculations required in [computational geometry](/Computational_geometry), all of which implicitly rely on zero's even status. Moreover, its divisibility extends beyond just 2; 0 is uniquely divisible by every single [power of 2](/Power_of_2), a property of paramount importance in the architecture of the [binary numeral system](/Binary_numeral_system) that forms the bedrock of modern computers. In a profound sense, one might even argue that 0 is, numerically speaking, the "most even" number of all. ( [Full article...](/Parity_of_zero) )

