One of Molyneux's celestial globes, which is displayed in [Middle Temple](/Middle_Temple) Library – from the frontispiece of the [Hakluyt Society](/Hakluyt_Society)'s 1889 reprint of A Learned Treatise of Globes, both Cœlestiall and Terrestriall , one of the English editions of Robert Hues' [Latin](/Latin) work Tractatus de Globis (1594)

[Emery Molyneux](/Emery_Molyneux) (pronounced /ˈɛməri ˈmɒlɪnoʊ/ EM-ər-ee MOL-in-oh; died June 1598) was a notable English figure during the [Elizabethan era](/Elizabethan_era), distinguished as a master craftsman of [globes](/Globe), sophisticated [mathematical instruments](/Mathematical_instruments), and military [ordnance](/Weapon). His terrestrial and celestial globes, which were first unveiled and published in 1592, hold a significant place in history as the very first to be both manufactured in England and crafted by an Englishman. This marked a pivotal moment for English cartography and instrument-making, previously dominated by continental European artisans.

Molyneux's reputation was firmly established as a skilled [mathematician](/Mathematician) and an expert maker of essential [mathematical instruments](/Mathematical_instruments), including precise [compasses](/Compass) for navigation and accurate [hourglasses](/Hourglass) for timekeeping. His expertise naturally brought him into contact with many of the era's most prominent intellectuals and adventurers. Among his acquaintances were the influential writer [Richard Hakluyt](/Richard_Hakluyt), whose works documented global exploration, and esteemed mathematicians like [Robert Hues](/Robert_Hues) and [Edward Wright](/Edward_Wright_(mathematician)), who were at the forefront of navigational science. Molyneux also forged connections with legendary explorers of the age, including [Thomas Cavendish](/Thomas_Cavendish), the circumnavigator, [Francis Drake](/Francis_Drake), the famed privateer, [Walter Raleigh](/Walter_Raleigh), the courtier and adventurer, and [John Davis](/John_Davis_(English_explorer)), the Arctic explorer. It was likely Davis who introduced Molyneux to his own patron, William Sanderson, a wealthy London merchant who ultimately provided the bulk of the financing for the ambitious construction of Molyneux's globes. Upon their completion, these magnificent globes were presented with due ceremony to [Elizabeth I](/Elizabeth_I) herself, a testament to their perceived national importance. Larger, more elaborate versions of the globes were subsequently acquired by royalty, various noblemen, and leading academic institutions, serving as symbols of prestige and scientific advancement. Concurrently, smaller, more portable versions were produced and purchased for their practical utility as navigational aids by sailors and students, proving invaluable for charting courses across the burgeoning global trade routes. A key innovation in Molyneux's globes was their construction in a manner that rendered them remarkably unaffected by the pervasive humidity at sea, a crucial improvement that significantly enhanced their durability and reliability. This practical advantage led to their widespread adoption and general use on ships, solidifying Molyneux's legacy as a pioneer in practical mathematics and global navigation. ( [Full article...](/Emery_Molyneux) )

