[Theodore John Kaczynski](/Ted_Kaczynski) (pronounced /kəˈzɪnski/ ⓘ kə-ZIN-skee; born May 22, 1942 – died June 10, 2023), infamous as the Unabomber (pronounced /ˈjuːnəbɒmər/ ⓘ YOO-nə-bom-ər), presents a stark, unsettling paradox: an American [mathematician](/Mathematician) and philosopher who devolved into a [domestic terrorist](/Domestic_terrorism_in_the_United_States). A genuine mathematics [prodigy](/Child_prodigy) from an early age, Kaczynski's trajectory took a dark turn. He abruptly abandoned a promising academic career in 1969, choosing instead to pursue a profoundly [reclusive](/Reclusive), almost entirely self-sufficient [primitive lifestyle](/Simple_living), which tragically morphed into a terrifying [lone wolf terrorism](/Lone_wolf_terrorism) campaign.

Between 1978 and 1995, Kaczynski unleashed a nationwide [mail bombing](/Mail_bomb) campaign, meticulously targeting individuals whom he perceived as advancing [modern technology](/Modern_technology) and contributing to the relentless destruction of the [natural environment](/Natural_environment). This reign of terror resulted in the murder of 3 people and injuries to 23 others, leaving a chilling legacy of fear and intellectual extremism. During this period, he authored a sprawling, approximately 35,000-word [manifesto](/Manifesto) and [social critique](/Social_critique) titled [Industrial Society and Its Future](/Industrial_Society_and_Its_Future), published in 1995. In this disturbing treatise, Kaczynski articulated a radical philosophy that vehemently opposed all forms of technology, rejected both [leftism](/Leftism) and [fascism](/Fascism) as equally detrimental, advocated for a return to cultural primitivism, and ultimately called for violent [revolution](/Revolution) as the only means to dismantle the oppressive industrial system he so despised. His case remains a haunting example of how profound intellectual capability can be twisted into destructive ideological fanaticism. ( [Full article...](/Ted_Kaczynski) )

