[Marian Adam Rejewski](/Marian_Rejewski) (Polish: [&#91;ˈmarjan rɛˈjɛfskʲi&#93;](/Help:IPA/Polish) ⓘ; born 16 August 1905 – died 13 February 1980) was a Polish [mathematician](/Mathematician) and a visionary [cryptologist](/Cryptography) whose extraordinary intellectual prowess proved instrumental in altering the course of World War II. In late 1932, with only limited, albeit crucial, documents obtained covertly by [French military intelligence](/French_secret_service), Rejewski achieved the seemingly impossible: he reconstructed the internal wiring and operational logic of the German military's highly sophisticated [Enigma cipher machine](/Enigma_machine) without ever having seen one. This was a feat of pure mathematical deduction and cryptographic genius.

Over the subsequent, nearly seven years, Rejewski, collaborating with his equally brilliant fellow mathematician-cryptologists [Jerzy Różycki](/Jerzy_Różycki) and [Henryk Zygalski], meticulously working at the [Polish General Staff](/Polish_General_Staff)'s [Cipher Bureau](/Cipher_Bureau_(Poland)), continuously refined and developed groundbreaking techniques and innovative equipment specifically designed for the decryption of the Enigma ciphers. Their work was a relentless intellectual arms race, as the Germans consistently introduced modifications to their Enigma machines and encryption procedures, forcing the Polish team to constantly adapt and innovate. Among Rejewski's most significant and enduring contributions to this monumental effort were the creation of the [cryptologic card catalog](/Card_catalog_(cryptology)), a systematic method for categorizing and analyzing Enigma settings, and the invention of the [cryptologic bomb](/Cryptologic_bomb), an electromechanical device specifically engineered to rapidly discover the daily settings of the Enigma machine. These inventions were pivotal, providing the Allies with an invaluable, albeit often precarious, window into German military communications, a contribution that demonstrably shortened the war and saved countless lives. ( [Full article...](/Marian_Rejewski) )

