High-precision test of general relativity by the [Cassini](/Cassini-Huygens) space probe (artist's impression): radio signals sent between the Earth and the probe (green wave) are [delayed](/Shapiro_effect) by the warping of [spacetime](/Spacetime) (blue lines) due to the [Sun](/Sun)'s mass.

[General relativity](/Introduction_to_general_relativity) is not merely a theory; it is a profound reconceptualization of [gravitation](/Gravitation), meticulously developed by the singular intellect of [Albert Einstein](/Albert_Einstein) over a period spanning from 1907 to 1915. At its core, the theory posits that the gravitational effect we observe between masses is not the result of a mysterious, invisible force, but rather a direct consequence of these masses physically warping the very fabric of [spacetime](/Spacetime) itself. Imagine a bowling ball on a stretched rubber sheet; the indentation it creates is analogous to how mass distorts spacetime, and other objects "fall" into this indentation, mimicking gravity.

By the dawn of the 20th century, [Newton's law of universal gravitation](/Newton%27s_law_of_universal_gravitation) had reigned supreme for over two centuries, universally accepted as the definitive and valid description of the gravitational force acting between massive objects. In Newton's elegant yet ultimately incomplete model, gravity was conceptualized as an inherent attractive force, a pull, between any two objects possessing mass. While Newton himself famously expressed discomfort and puzzlement over the "unknown nature" of this force – how it could act across vast empty space without any apparent medium – his foundational framework proved extraordinarily successful in accurately describing and predicting the motion of celestial bodies and terrestrial objects alike. General Relativity, however, provided the mechanism that Newton lacked, transforming gravity from a mysterious force into a geometric property of the universe. ( [Full article...](/Introduction_to_general_relativity) )

