In [classical mechanics](/Classical_mechanics), the [Laplace–Runge–Lenz vector](/Laplace%E2%80%93Runge%E2%80%93Lenz_vector) (often abbreviated as the LRL vector) stands as a remarkably insightful [vector](/Vector_(geometric)) quantity used primarily to precisely delineate both the shape and the orientation of the [orbit](/Orbit_(celestial_mechanics)) of one [astronomical body](/Astronomical_body) around another. This could be, for instance, a [binary star](/Binary_star) system where two stars orbit a common center of mass, or a planet tracing its path around a central star. For any system comprising [two bodies interacting](/Two-body_problem) exclusively through [Newtonian gravity](/Newton%27s_law_of_universal_gravitation), the LRL vector possesses a profound property: it is a [constant of motion](/Constant_of_motion). This means its value remains precisely the same regardless of where it is calculated along the entire orbit; equivalently, the LRL vector is said to be [conserved](/Conservation_law). More broadly, the LRL vector maintains its conserved status in all physical problems where two bodies interact via a [central force](/Central_force) that diminishes with the [inverse square](/Inverse_square_law) of the distance separating them. Such fundamental problems are universally known as [Kepler problems](/Kepler_problem), named after the astronomer whose laws describe planetary motion.

A classic and highly significant example of a Kepler problem is the [hydrogen atom](/Hydrogen_atom). This system, consisting of a single proton and a single electron, is governed by [Coulomb's law](/Coulomb%27s_law) of [electrostatics](/Electrostatics), which also describes an inverse-square central force. Historically, the LRL vector played a truly essential role in the very first [quantum mechanical](/Quantum_mechanical) derivation of the [spectrum](/Atomic_emission_spectrum) of the hydrogen atom. This groundbreaking achievement occurred even before the full development and widespread adoption of the more familiar [Schrödinger equation](/Schrödinger_equation). While this earlier, LRL-vector-based approach offered remarkable insights into the quantum nature of the atom, it is, curiously, rarely employed in modern quantum mechanics pedagogy or research today, largely superseded by more general and versatile methods. ( [Full article...](/Laplace%E2%20%E2%80%93Runge%E2%80%93Lenz_vector) )

