In the elegant realm of [Euclidean plane geometry](/Euclidean_geometry), [Apollonius's problem](/Problem_of_Apollonius) stands as a classical challenge: the construction of circles that are precisely [tangent](/Tangent) to three given circles within a plane, as vividly illustrated in Figure&#160;1. This renowned geometrical puzzle was originally posed and meticulously solved by [Apollonius of Perga](/Apollonius_of_Perga), a brilliant Greek geometer who lived from approximately 262 BC to 190 BC. His original work detailing this solution, titled Ἐπαφαί (Epaphaí, meaning "Tangencies"), has unfortunately been [lost](/Lost_literary_work) to the ravages of time. However, a crucial 4th-century AD report by [Pappus of Alexandria](/Pappus_of_Alexandria) provides a surviving account of Apollonius's remarkable results, ensuring his legacy.

Generically, when three distinct circles are given, there exist precisely eight different circles that can be tangent to all three of them simultaneously, as depicted in Figure&#160;2. This multiplicity of solutions arises from the four distinct ways one can conceptually divide the three given circles into two subsets. In the 16th century, the Dutch mathematician [Adriaan van Roomen](/Adriaan_van_Roomen) successfully tackled the problem, employing intersecting [hyperbolas](/Hyperbola). However, his method, while effective, relied on techniques that extended beyond the strictures of classical [straightedge and compass](/Straightedge_and_compass) constructions. It was [François Viète](/Fran%C3%A7ois_Vi%C3%A8te), a French mathematician, who later devised a solution using only a straightedge and compass. Viète's ingenious approach involved exploiting various [limiting cases](/Limiting_case_(mathematics)): he demonstrated that any of the three given circles could be conceptually shrunk to a zero radius (effectively becoming a point) or expanded to an infinite radius (transforming into a line). This method, which simplifies more complex scenarios by reducing them to simpler limiting cases, is widely regarded as a plausible reconstruction of Apollonius's original, lost methodology. The method pioneered by van Roomen was further simplified and refined by the prodigious [Isaac Newton](/Isaac_Newton), who elegantly demonstrated that Apollonius's problem is mathematically equivalent to the task of finding a specific position based on the differences of its distances to three known points. This fundamental equivalence has found tangible modern applications in various navigation and positioning systems, such as [LORAN](/LORAN), proving that ancient geometric puzzles can unexpectedly underpin contemporary technology. ( [Full article...](/Problem_of_Apollonius) )

