1753 portrait

[Leonhard Euler](/Leonhard_Euler) (pronounced /ˈɔɪlər/ OY-lər; born 15 April 1707 – died 18 September 1783) was not merely a mathematician; he was a Swiss [polymath](/Polymath) of unparalleled breadth, whose intellectual pursuits spanned an astonishing array of disciplines. He was actively engaged as a mathematician, physicist, astronomer, logician, geographer, and even an engineer, demonstrating a truly universal genius. His contributions were foundational, as he effectively founded the studies of [graph theory](/Graph_theory), which examines networks of points and lines, and [topology](/Topology), the study of properties of spaces that are preserved under continuous deformations. Beyond these foundational achievements, Euler made profoundly influential discoveries in numerous other branches of mathematics, including the intricate structures of [analytic number theory](/Analytic_number_theory), the complex landscapes of [complex analysis](/Complex_analysis), and the infinitely precise mechanics of [infinitesimal calculus](/Infinitesimal_calculus).

Perhaps one of his most enduring legacies is his role in introducing and popularizing much of modern mathematical terminology and [notation](/Mathematical_notation), thereby standardizing the language of mathematics for generations to come. This includes the now-ubiquitous notion of a [mathematical function](/Mathematical_function). His intellectual reach extended far beyond pure abstraction; he is also renowned for his pioneering work in [mechanics](/Mechanics), the fluid dynamics of [fluid dynamics](/Fluid_dynamics), the principles of optics, the celestial mechanics of astronomy, and even the mathematical underpinnings of music theory. Indeed, Euler has been justly celebrated as a "universal genius" who "was fully equipped with almost unlimited powers of imagination, intellectual gifts and extraordinary memory," a description that barely scratches the surface of his prodigious output. He spent the majority of his adult life contributing to the scientific academies of [Saint Petersburg](/Saint_Petersburg), Russia, and in [Berlin](/Berlin), which was then the bustling capital of [Prussia](/Kingdom_of_Prussia).

Euler is widely credited for popularizing the use of the Greek letter π (lowercase [pi](/Pi_(letter))) to denote [the ratio of a circle's circumference to its diameter](/Pi), a constant now universally recognized. He was also the first to systematically employ the notation *f*(*x*) for the value of a function, a convention that revolutionized the clarity of mathematical expression. His introduction of the letter *i* to express the [imaginary unit](/Imaginary_unit) √−1 elegantly brought complex numbers into the mainstream. Furthermore, he popularized the Greek letter Σ (capital [sigma](/Sigma)) to concisely represent [summations](/Summation), and Δ (capital [delta](/Delta_(letter))) for denoting [finite differences](/Finite_difference). In geometry, he established the convention of using lowercase letters to represent the sides of a triangle while reserving capital letters for its angles, a system still in use today. He also provided the precise, current definition of the constant *e*, the base of the [natural logarithm], which is now eponymously known as [Euler's number](/Euler%27s_number). Beyond these monumental theoretical contributions, Euler made significant practical advancements in [applied mathematics](/Applied_mathematics) and [engineering](/Engineering), including his detailed studies of ships, which demonstrably improved navigation; his three comprehensive volumes on optics, which profoundly contributed to the design and optimization of [microscopes](/Microscope) and [telescopes]; and his groundbreaking analyses of beam bending and the critical loads columns can bear, foundational work in structural engineering. ( [Full article...](/Leonhard_Euler) )

