Image 13
The first 15,000 partial sums of 0 + 1 − 2 + 3 − 4 + ... The graph is situated with positive integers to the right and negative integers to the left.

In the often counter-intuitive world of [mathematics](/Mathematics), the expression [1 − 2 + 3 − 4 + ···](/1_%E2%88%92_2_%2B_3_%E2%88%92_4_%2B_%E2%8B%AF) represents an [infinite series](/Series_(mathematics)) whose terms are simply the successive [positive integers](/Positive_integer), but with their signs [alternating](/Alternating_series). Using the concise [sigma summation notation](/Summation), the sum of the first *m* terms of this series can be elegantly expressed as:

$${\displaystyle \sum _{n=1}^{m}n(-1)^{n-1}.}$$

This particular infinite series, as any rigorous analysis would confirm, unequivocally [diverges](/Divergent_series). This means that its sequence of [partial sums](/Partial_sum)—which progresses as (1, −1, 2, −2, 3, ...)—does not, and never will, tend towards any finite, stable [limit](/Limit_of_a_sequence). The sums oscillate wildly, never settling. Nonetheless, in the mid-18th century, the brilliant, audacious [Leonhard Euler](/Leonhard_Euler) famously penned an equation that he himself acknowledged to be deeply [paradoxical](/List_of_paradoxes):

$${\displaystyle 1-2+3-4+\cdots ={\frac {1}{4}}}.$$

This seemingly impossible result, derived through methods of regularization that extend beyond standard summation, continues to fascinate and challenge the very foundations of how we define and understand infinite sums, serving as a powerful reminder that intuition often falters at the edges of infinity. ( [Full article...](/1_%E2%88%92_2_%2B_3_%E2%88%92_4_%2B_%E2%8B%AF) )

