[Émile Michel Hyacinthe Lemoine](/%C3%89mile_Lemoine) (French: [&#91;emil ləmwan&#93;](/Help:IPA/French); born 22 November 1840 – died 21 February 1912) was a multifaceted French intellectual, primarily known as a [civil engineer](/Civil_engineer) by profession and a distinguished [mathematician](/Mathematician), with a particular specialization as a [geometer](/Geometer). His academic journey was marked by a diverse and rigorous education across several esteemed institutions, including the prestigious [Prytanée National Militaire](/Prytan%C3%A9e_National_Militaire) and, most notably, the highly selective [École Polytechnique](/%C3%89cole_Polytechnique), a bastion of scientific and engineering excellence. Following his graduation from the latter, Lemoine dedicated a brief period of his life to teaching, serving as a private tutor, a common path for brilliant minds before fully embarking on their chosen careers.

Lemoine's most enduring legacy in the mathematical world stems from his elegant proof of the existence of the [Lemoine point](/Lemoine_point)—also frequently referred to as the symmedian point—of a [triangle](/Triangle). This specific point, a geometric invariant, holds a unique and central position within the triangle, defined by the intersection of its symmedians. Beyond this notable achievement, his other significant mathematical contributions include the development of a systematic methodology he termed Géométrographie, which aimed to simplify complex geometric constructions. He also pioneered a method that ingeniously related intricate [algebraic](/Algebra) expressions to corresponding geometric objects, bridging two seemingly disparate branches of mathematics. Due to the pervasive influence and innovative nature of his work, which introduced many of the characteristic properties that define this specialized field, Émile Lemoine is deservedly recognized as a co-founder of modern triangle geometry. ( [Full article...](/%C3%89mile_Lemoine) )

