Cantor, c. &#8201;1910

[Georg Ferdinand Ludwig Philipp Cantor](/Georg_Cantor) (pronounced /ˈkæntɔːr/ KAN-tor; German: [&#91;ˈɡeːɔʁk ˈfɛʁdinant ˈluːtvɪç ˈfiːlɪp ˈkantoːɐ̯&#93;](/Help:IPA/Standard_German); born 3 March&#160;[O.S.](/Old_Style_and_New_Style_dates) 19 February&#93;&#160;1845&#160;– died 6 January 1918) was a mathematician whose audacious intellectual explorations played an absolutely pivotal role in the creation and establishment of [set theory](/Set_theory). This revolutionary framework has since ascended to the status of a [fundamental theory](/Foundations_of_mathematics) within mathematics, providing the bedrock for much of modern analysis and logic. Cantor's genius lay in his ability to formalize concepts that had previously been considered vague or paradoxical. He meticulously established the profound importance of [one-to-one correspondence](/One-to-one_correspondence) as a means of comparing the sizes of sets, even infinite ones. Through this, he rigorously defined what it meant for sets to be [infinite](/Infinite_set) and [well-ordered sets](/Well-order), paving the way for understanding different "sizes" of infinity. His most startling and significant achievement was proving that the [real numbers](/Real_number) are demonstrably more numerous—a larger infinity—than the [natural numbers](/Natural_number). This groundbreaking method of proof, known as Cantor's diagonal argument, implicitly revealed the existence of an entire hierarchy, an [infinity](/Infinity) of infinities, each larger than the last. He further defined the precise concepts of [cardinal](/Cardinal_number) and [ordinal](/Ordinal_number) numbers and developed a coherent arithmetic for these transfinite quantities. The implications of Cantor's work were not merely mathematical; they were of immense philosophical interest, a fact he was acutely aware of and often grappled with.

Unsurprisingly, at its inception, Cantor's theory of [transfinite numbers](/Transfinite_number) was widely regarded as deeply counter-intuitive, even shocking, to many of his contemporaries. This radical departure from established mathematical thought met with fierce resistance from influential figures such as [Leopold Kronecker](/Leopold_Kronecker) and [Henri Poincaré], and later from [Hermann Weyl](/Hermann_Weyl) and [L._E._J._Brouwer]. Even the philosopher [Ludwig Wittgenstein](/Ludwig_Wittgenstein) raised significant [philosophical objections](/Philosophical_objections_to_Cantor%27s_theory) to its tenets. For Cantor, a devout [Lutheran Christian](/Lutheran_Christian), his theory was not merely an intellectual construct but a profound truth, one he believed had been communicated to him directly by God. This conviction, however, did not shield him from theological controversy. Some [Christian theologians](/Christian_theology), particularly those from the [neo-Scholasticism](/Neo-Scholasticism) tradition, perceived Cantor's work as a direct challenge to the unique, absolute infinity inherent in the nature of God. On one notorious occasion, the theory of transfinite numbers was even equated with [pantheism](/Pantheism)—a proposition that Cantor vehemently and repeatedly rejected. Yet, not all theologians were antagonistic to Cantor's revolutionary ideas; prominent neo-scholastic philosopher Konstantin Gutberlet (de; it) actually championed his work, and Cardinal [Johann Baptist Franzelin](/Johann_Baptist_Franzelin) ultimately accepted it as a valid theory, especially after Cantor provided crucial clarifications that reconciled his mathematical infinities with theological concepts of the divine. ( [Full article...](/Georg_Cantor) )

