three lines connecting corresponding vertices of a larger triangle on the left and a smaller one on the right converge at a point further to the right called the "center of perspectivity"

[Desargues's theorem](/Desargues%27s_theorem)
Credit:&#160;[User:Jujutacular](/User:Jujutacular), based on an original by [User:DynaBlast](/User:DynaBlast)

In the elegant and often counter-intuitive realm of [projective geometry](/Projective_geometry), [Desargues' theorem](/Desargues%27_theorem) stands as a fundamental and visually striking principle. It articulates a profound relationship between two triangles, stating that they are in [perspective](/Perspective_(geometry)) axially [if and only if](/If_and_only_if) they are in perspective centrally. This "if and only if" condition is the hallmark of a deep, symmetrical equivalence. To unpack this, consider the lines formed by extending the corresponding sides of the two triangles. These lines, when extended, will meet in pairs at three distinct [collinear points](/Line_(geometry))—points that all lie on a single straight line. This line is known as the axis of perspectivity. Concurrently, if one draws lines connecting corresponding pairs of [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)) (corners) from the two triangles, these three lines will invariably converge and meet at a single, unique point. This point of convergence is termed the center of perspectivity. Desargues' theorem thus reveals a beautiful duality: the geometric configuration of lines and points is either entirely aligned along a central point *and* an axial line, or it is aligned along neither. It's a statement about the inherent order that emerges from seemingly complex arrangements in space, a testament to the power of geometric abstraction.

