Image 1
A set of 20 points in a 10 × 10 grid, with no three points in a line.
The [no-three-in-line problem](/No-three-in-line_problem), a deceptively simple yet profoundly challenging puzzle in [discrete geometry](/Discrete_geometry), asks a fundamental question: what is the maximum number of points one can meticulously place within an *n* × *n* grid such that no three of these points ever lie on the same straight line? It's important to note that this constraint applies to lines of *all* possible [slopes](/Slope), not merely those conveniently aligned with the grid's axes. First introduced to the mathematical community by the renowned puzzle-creator [Henry Dudeney](/Henry_Dudeney) in 1900, this problem has since captivated mathematicians for over a century. Indeed, Brass, Moser, and Pach have aptly characterized it as "one of the oldest and most extensively studied geometric questions concerning lattice points," highlighting its enduring allure and complexity.

The problem has a straightforward upper bound: at most *2n* points can be placed. This limit is derived from the elegant [pigeonhole principle](/Pigeonhole_principle), which dictates that if *2n + 1* points were placed in an *n* × *n* grid, then at least one row, column, or diagonal would inevitably contain three or more collinear points. While the problem has been definitively solved with *2n* points for every *n* up to *58*, leading to perfectly constructed arrangements, it is a widely held conjecture that for grids of sufficiently large size, it becomes impossible to place as many as *2n* points without violating the "no-three-in-line" rule. In other words, the *2n* bound is thought to be unattainable for very large *n*. Current known methods, while systematic and effective, can only manage to place a linearly proportional number of points in grids of arbitrary size. However, even the most sophisticated of these methods consistently place slightly fewer than *1.5n* points, falling short of the *2n* ideal, leaving a significant gap and the problem tantalizingly unsolved for large *n*. ( [Full article...](/No-three-in-line_problem) )

