Image 2

In [mathematics](/Mathematics), the [Pythagorean theorem](/Pythagorean_theorem), or Pythagoras's theorem as it is also known, is far more than a mere equation; it is a fundamental, foundational relation within [Euclidean geometry](/Euclidean_geometry) that elegantly connects the lengths of the three sides of any [right triangle](/Right_triangle). Its enduring statement is simple yet profound: the area of the [square](/Square) constructed on the side that is the [hypotenuse](/Hypotenuse)—the longest side, always positioned opposite the [right angle](/Right_angle)—is precisely equal to the sum of the areas of the squares constructed on the other two sides. This geometric truth has resonated for millennia.

The theorem is most commonly expressed as a concise [equation](/Equation) relating the lengths of the two shorter sides, *a* and *b*, to the length of the hypotenuse, *c*. This universally recognized formula is often termed the Pythagorean equation:

$${\displaystyle a^{2}+b^{2}=c^{2}.}$$

This enduring geometric principle is, of course, named in honor of the ancient [Greek](/Ancient_Greece) philosopher and mathematician [Pythagoras](/Pythagoras), who was born around 570 BC, though its origins and understanding likely predate him in various cultures. What is truly remarkable about this theorem is not just its fundamental importance, but the sheer volume and diversity of its [proofs](/Mathematical_proof). It has been proven countless times, by an astonishing array of different methods—possibly more than any other mathematical theorem in history. These proofs span a vast intellectual landscape, encompassing both intuitive [geometric](/Geometry) demonstrations that rely on visual rearrangement of areas, and rigorous [algebraic](/Algebra) derivations that manipulate symbols and equations. Some of these proofs date back thousands of years, discovered independently across different civilizations, attesting to the theorem's universal appeal and self-evident truth to the discerning mind. ( [Full article...](/Pythagorean_theorem) )

