Image 3

A kite, showing its pairs of equal-length sides and its inscribed circle.

In [Euclidean geometry](/Euclidean_geometry), a [kite](/Kite_(geometry)) is a distinct type of [quadrilateral](/Quadrilateral)—a four-sided polygon—defined by a unique characteristic: it possesses [reflection symmetry](/Reflection_symmetry) across one of its [diagonals](/Diagonal). This inherent symmetry dictates many of its properties. Specifically, a kite will always have two pairs of sides that are equal in length, and these equal-length sides are invariably adjacent to each other. Furthermore, due to this same axis of symmetry, a kite also features two equal angles, which are located opposite each other and lie between the unequal sides. Kites are occasionally referred to as deltoids, though this term can lead to confusion as the word "deltoid" may also refer to a [deltoid curve](/Deltoid_curve), a completely unrelated geometric object that is sometimes explored in the context of quadrilaterals, but has a different definition. A kite can also take on a non-convex form, in which case it is often specifically called a dart, particularly when one of its interior angles exceeds 180 degrees.

Every kite, regardless of its specific shape, is fundamentally an [orthodiagonal quadrilateral](/Orthodiagonal_quadrilateral), meaning its two diagonals always intersect at a perfect right angle. Additionally, when a kite is convex (i.e., it doesn't have any interior angles greater than 180 degrees), it also qualifies as a [tangential quadrilateral](/Tangential_quadrilateral), implying that all four of its sides are tangent to a single [inscribed circle](/Incircle). In fact, the convex kites are precisely those quadrilaterals that simultaneously exhibit both orthodiagonal and tangential properties. This category of shapes includes several well-known special cases: the [right kites](/Right_kite), which are defined by having two opposite right angles; the [rhombi](/Rhombus), which possess two diagonal axes of symmetry and thus have all four sides equal in length; and the [squares](/Square), which represent the ultimate intersection of these properties, being special cases of both right kites and rhombi, embodying perfect symmetry and regularity. ( [Full article...](/Kite_(geometry)) )

