Image 5

A Pythagorean tiling

A [Pythagorean tiling](/Pythagorean_tiling), also known more descriptively as a two squares tessellation, is a captivating arrangement that covers a [Euclidean](/Euclidean_geometry) plane entirely and without gaps using [squares](/Square_(geometry)) of precisely two different sizes. What makes this tiling particularly distinctive is its specific configuration: each square within the pattern is designed to touch four squares of the *other* size on all four of its sides. This creates a visually intricate and mathematically compelling repeating pattern. The tiling derives its evocative name from the fact that numerous elegant [proofs](/Mathematical_proof) of the venerable [Pythagorean&#160;theorem](/Pythagorean_theorem) are ingeniously based upon this very geometric arrangement, demonstrating a profound connection between visual pattern and fundamental mathematical truth.

Beyond its theoretical significance, the Pythagorean tiling finds common, practical application as a pattern for [floor tiles](/Tile), where its alternating sizes create a dynamic yet harmonious aesthetic. When used in this context, it is also frequently referred to as a hopscotch pattern or a pinwheel pattern. However, it is crucial not to confuse this with the mathematical [pinwheel tiling](/Pinwheel_tiling), which is an entirely unrelated and far more complex aperiodic pattern. This particular tiling exhibits a striking four-way [rotational symmetry](/Rotational_symmetry) around the center of each of its constituent squares, meaning it looks identical after rotations of 90, 180, and 270 degrees. Furthermore, when the ratio of the side lengths of the two different sized squares is an [irrational number](/Irrational_number)—such as the famous [golden ratio](/Golden_ratio) (φ ≈ 1.618)—its cross-sections generate intricate [aperiodic sequences](/Aperiodic_tiling). These sequences possess a recursive structure remarkably similar to that found in the [Fibonacci word](/Fibonacci_word), hinting at deeper connections between geometry, number theory, and discrete mathematics. The concept of this tiling has also been extended and generalized to three dimensions, exploring how similar patterns of interlocking cubes of different sizes might fill space. ( [Full article...](/Pythagorean_tiling) )

