Image 6
The [equals sign](/Equals_sign), used to represent equality symbolically in an [equation](/Equation)

In [mathematics](/Mathematics), [equality](/Equality_(mathematics)) is a relationship of fundamental importance, serving as the bedrock for countless theorems and operations. It is a precise statement that two distinct [quantities](/Quantities) or [expressions](/Expression_(mathematics)) possess precisely the same value, or that they represent one and the same [mathematical object](/Mathematical_object). The relationship of equality between an entity A and an entity B is universally denoted by the iconic [equals sign](/Equals_sign) as A &#160;=&#160; B, and is read aloud as "A equals B." A written expression that asserts equality is broadly termed an [equation](/Equation) or, depending on its specific context and generality, an [identity](/Identity_(mathematics)). Conversely, two objects that are not equal are formally described as [distinct](/Not_equal).

Equality is often considered a [primitive notion](/Primitive_notion) within mathematics, meaning it is so fundamental that it resists formal definition in terms of simpler concepts. Instead, it is informally characterized as "a relation each thing bears to itself and nothing else." This seemingly straightforward characterization is, upon closer inspection, notably circular ("nothing else"), reflecting the inherent conceptual difficulty in fully and non-recursively characterizing such a basic concept. Despite this definitional challenge, the basic properties that govern equality—namely [reflexivity](/Reflexive_relation) (A = A), [symmetry](/Symmetric_relation) (if A = B then B = A), and [transitivity](/Transitive_relation) (if A = B and B = C then A = C)—have been intuitively understood and applied since at least the era of the [ancient Greeks](/Ancient_Greeks). However, it wasn't until the late 19th century that these properties were formally and symbolically stated as general attributes of relations, a significant contribution made by the Italian mathematician [Giuseppe Peano](/Giuseppe_Peano). Other crucial properties, such as [substitution](/Substitution_(logic)) (if A = B, then A can replace B in any true statement) and [function application](/Function_application) (if A = B, then f(A) = f(B)), were not formally articulated until the rigorous development of [symbolic logic](/Symbolic_logic) in the early 20th century, underscoring the long journey from intuitive understanding to formal axiomatic precision. ( [Full article...](/Equality_(mathematics)) )

