Image 7
An illustration of the lightbulb problem, where one is searching for a broken bulb among six lightbulbs. Here, the first three are connected to a power supply, and they light up (A). This indicates that the broken bulb must be one of the last three (B). If instead the bulbs did not light up, one could be sure that the broken bulb was among the first three. Continuing this procedure can locate the broken bulb in no more than three tests, compared to a maximum of six tests if the bulbs are checked individually.

In the intertwined disciplines of [statistics](/Statistics) and [combinatorial mathematics](/Combinatorics), [group testing](/Group_testing) refers to any systematic procedure designed to streamline the task of identifying specific objects from a larger collection. Rather than performing individual tests on each item, group testing intelligently pools items into groups, conducting tests on these aggregates to infer properties about their individual components. This field, though relatively young, was first rigorously studied by the American economist and mathematician [Robert Dorfman](/Robert_Dorfman) in 1943, initially in the context of efficiently identifying syphilitic men among U.S. soldiers during World War II. Since then, it has evolved significantly, becoming a dynamic and active area of research today, with a wide range of practical applications across various domains.

A readily understandable illustration of the power of group testing involves the classic "light bulb problem." Imagine a string of light bulbs connected in series, where it is known definitively that precisely one of these bulbs is broken. The objective is to pinpoint the faulty bulb using the absolute minimum number of tests, where a "test" constitutes connecting a subset of the bulbs to a power supply and observing whether they illuminate. A naive, brute-force approach would involve testing each bulb individually, which, in a string of *N* bulbs, would require up to *N* tests in the worst case. However, when confronted with a large number of bulbs, a group testing strategy proves far more efficient. For example, by connecting the first half of the bulbs to the power supply simultaneously, one can immediately determine which half of the string contains the broken bulb. If the first half lights up, the fault must lie in the second half; if they do not light up, the fault is within the first half. In either scenario, this single test effectively rules out half of the bulbs from further consideration. By iteratively applying this divide-and-conquer strategy, the broken bulb can be located significantly faster than individual testing, demonstrating the profound efficiency gains offered by intelligent grouping. ( [Full article...](/Group_testing) )

