Image 8
The boundary of a Reuleaux triangle is a constant width curve based on an equilateral triangle. All points on a side are equidistant from the opposite vertex.
A [Reuleaux triangle](/Reuleaux_triangle) (pronounced [ʁœlo]) is a captivating example of a [curved triangle](/Circular_triangle) that possesses the remarkable property of [constant width](/Curve_of_constant_width). It is, in fact, the simplest and most widely recognized curve of constant width apart from the ubiquitous circle. This unique shape is geometrically constructed from the intersection of three equally sized [circular disks](/Circle), where the center of each disk is precisely situated on the boundary of the other two. The defining characteristic of constant width means that if you were to measure the distance between any two parallel [supporting lines](/Supporting_line) that touch the curve, that distance would remain exactly the same, irrespective of the orientation of those lines. Because of this intriguing property, the Reuleaux triangle provides an elegant answer to a classic practical riddle: "Other than a circle, what shape can a [manhole cover](/Manhole_cover) be made so that it cannot fall down through the hole it covers?" Its constant width ensures it can never be rotated and dropped through an opening of the same dimension.

These intriguing shapes are eponymously named after [Franz Reuleaux](/Franz_Reuleaux), a prominent 19th-century German engineer who was a pioneer in the systematic study of machines designed to translate one type of motion into another. Reuleaux notably incorporated these triangles into his innovative mechanical designs. However, the geometric properties of these shapes were, in fact, understood and utilized long before Reuleaux's time. They can be found in the intricate designs of [Gothic](/Gothic_architecture) church windows, where their unique curves provided both structural integrity and aesthetic beauty. [Leonardo da Vinci](/Leonardo_da_Vinci) famously employed a variation of the Reuleaux triangle for an [octant projection](/Octant_projection) in his world maps, demonstrating its utility in cartography. Even [Leonhard Euler](/Leonhard_Euler) explored these constant-width shapes in his extensive mathematical investigations. Today, the practical applications of the Reuleaux triangle extend into diverse fields, lending its distinctive shape to [guitar picks](/Guitar_pick) for consistent feel, [fire hydrant](/Fire_hydrant) nuts for easy gripping, specific designs of [pencils](/Pencil), and specialized [drill bits](/Drill_bit) engineered for drilling [filleted](/Fillet_(mechanics)) square holes with remarkable precision. Its elegant form also finds a place in modern graphic design, influencing the shapes of various signs and corporate logos, proving that abstract geometry can have surprising real-world utility and aesthetic appeal. ( [Full article...](/Reuleaux_triangle) )

