Image 9
A unit distance graph with 16 vertices and 40 edges
In [mathematics](/Mathematics), particularly within the specialized domain of [geometric graph theory](/Geometric_graph_theory), a [unit distance graph](/Unit_distance_graph) is a specific type of [graph](/Graph_(discrete_mathematics)) constructed from a collection of points meticulously placed in the [Euclidean plane](/Euclidean_plane). The defining characteristic is that two points in this collection are connected by an edge *if and only if* the precise distance between them is exactly one unit. To meticulously differentiate these graphs from a broader, more permissive definition that might allow some non-adjacent pairs of vertices to also be at a distance of one, they are sometimes more precisely termed strict unit distance graphs or faithful unit distance graphs. As a [hereditary family of graphs](/Hereditary_property)—meaning any induced subgraph of a unit distance graph is also a unit distance graph—they can be characterized by identifying a set of [forbidden induced subgraphs](/Forbidden_graph_characterization), structures that simply cannot appear within them. The family of unit distance graphs is rich and diverse, encompassing various well-known graph types such as the [cactus graphs](/Cactus_graph) (where every edge belongs to at most one cycle), the [matchstick graphs](/Matchstick_graph) (planar graphs that can be drawn with edges as unit-length line segments), and [penny graphs](/Penny_graph) (contact graphs of non-overlapping unit circles), and the [hypercube graphs](/Hypercube_graph). It's worth noting that the [generalized Petersen graphs](/Generalized_Petersen_graph) are considered non-strict unit distance graphs, as they can be embedded in the plane with unit distances, but not all unit-distance pairs are necessarily connected.

Despite their seemingly simple definition, unit distance graphs are at the heart of several profound and stubbornly unsolved problems in discrete geometry. One such challenge, posed by the legendary [Paul Erdős](/Paul_Erd%C5%91s), asks for the maximum number of edges a unit distance graph on *n* vertices can possess. The current best known [lower bound](/Lower_bound) for this quantity is slightly above linear in *n*, meaning it grows a bit faster than *n*. However, this is still remarkably far from the established [upper bound](/Upper_bound), which is proportional to *n*^(4/3), indicating a significant gap in our understanding. Another infamous open problem, known as the [Hadwiger–Nelson problem](/Hadwiger%E2%80%93Nelson_problem), concerns the number of colors required to [color](/Graph_coloring) unit distance graphs such that no two adjacent vertices share the same color. It has been proven that some unit distance graphs necessitate at least five colors, while it is also known that every unit distance graph can be colored with seven colors, leaving the exact chromatic number (either 5, 6, or 7) an open question. Furthermore, a fascinating property of these graphs is that for every [algebraic number](/Algebraic_number) α, it is possible to construct a unit distance graph containing two vertices that are separated by precisely the distance α. Finally, according to the elegant [Beckman–Quarles theorem](/Beckman%E2%80%93Quarles_theorem), the only transformations of the plane that inherently preserve the entire class of unit distance graphs are the [isometries](/Euclidean_plane_isometry)—that is, transformations that preserve distances, such as rotations, reflections, and translations. ( [Full article...](/Unit_distance_graph) )

