[Alexandrov's theorem on polyhedra](/Alexandrov%27s_theorem_on_polyhedra) is a profound and elegant [rigidity theorem](/Rigidity_(mathematics)) within the field of mathematics, offering deep insights into the nature of three-dimensional [convex polyhedra](/Convex_polyhedron). Published in the 1940s by the Soviet mathematician [Aleksandr Danilovich Aleksandrov](/Aleksandr_Danilovich_Aleksandrov), after whom it is named, the theorem provides a meticulous characterization of these polyhedra based solely on the intrinsic distances between points on their surfaces. Essentially, it asserts that the complete metric space of surface distances uniquely determines the shape of a convex polyhedron.

The theorem carries significant implications. Firstly, it implies a one-to-one correspondence between the geometric shape of a convex polyhedron and the metric structure of its surface. This means that any two convex polyhedra that possess distinct shapes from each other will necessarily exhibit distinct [metric spaces](/Metric_space) when considering the distances between points along their surfaces. Conversely, if two convex polyhedra have metrically identical surfaces, they must be congruent. Secondly, and perhaps more powerfully, Alexandrov's theorem provides a comprehensive characterization of precisely which metric spaces can arise from the surface distances on polyhedra. It gives necessary and sufficient conditions for a given metric space to be realizable as the surface of a convex polyhedron, effectively defining the boundaries of what is geometrically possible in this domain. This theorem is a cornerstone in the study of discrete geometry and the geometry of surfaces, demonstrating how local metric properties can rigidly determine global geometric forms. ( [Full article...](/Alexandrov%27s_theorem_on_polyhedra) )

