Basic Math is an [educational video game](/Educational_video_game) programmed by Gary Palmer and published by [Atari, Inc.](/Atari,_Inc.) for the [Atari Video Computer System](/Atari_2600). The game features a series of ten [arithmetic](/Arithmetic) problems involving [addition](/Addition), [subtraction](/Subtraction), [multiplication](/Multiplication), or [division](/Division_(mathematics)). The player can edit different gameplay modes to alter how the numbers in the problem are chosen, or if their questions are timed. The game was released in September 1977 as one of the earliest releases for the Atari VCS.

[Basic Math (video game)](/Basic_Math_(video_game)) stands as a rather humble artifact from the dawn of the video game era, an [educational video game](/Educational_video_game) meticulously programmed by Gary Palmer and published by the nascent [Atari, Inc.](/Atari,_Inc.) for their pioneering [Atari Video Computer System](/Atari_2600). Released in September 1977, it was among the very earliest titles for the Atari VCS, attempting to graft rudimentary [arithmetic](/Arithmetic) onto the nascent medium of interactive digital entertainment. The game's premise was straightforward, almost painfully so: it presented the player with a series of ten problems encompassing the four fundamental operations of [addition](/Addition), [subtraction](/Subtraction), [multiplication](/Multiplication), or [division](/Division_(mathematics)). To inject a semblance of variability, players were granted the ability to edit various gameplay modes, allowing them to customize how the numbers within the problems were generated, or to introduce a timed element to their mathematical challenges.

Gary Palmer, the programmer behind *Basic Math*, is primarily known for this single contribution to the VCS library. His work at Atari initially involved creating essential debugging stations for game developers, and he later lent his expertise to the development of the more advanced [Atari 400/800](/Atari_8-bit_computers) line of personal computers. *Basic Math* holds the distinction of being the first educational video game specifically developed for the VCS, a pioneering, if uninspired, effort. Its release coincided with a nascent trend in educational gaming, as other companies also launched arithmetic-themed cartridges in the same year for competing systems like the [Fairchild Channel F](/Fairchild_Channel_F) and the [RCA Studio II](/RCA_Studio_II). However, both contemporary reviews from the late 1970s and retrospective analyses have consistently been, shall we say, unenthused by the game. Common criticisms invariably centered on its conspicuously poor quality graphics, which even for the era were considered subpar, and a general lack of engaging gameplay or intuitive control, rendering the educational experience less than captivating. It seems even in its infancy, the art of making math "fun" through video games was a challenge rarely met with success. ( [Full article...](/Basic_Math_(video_game)) )

