A deeper dive into the trivial and the profound, a curated collection of facts that might just linger in the recesses of your mind.

Did you know...

• ...that the [axiom of choice](/Axiom_of_choice) is [logically independent](/Logically_independent) of the other axioms of [Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory](/Zermelo%E2%80%93Fraenkel_set_theory)? This means you can neither prove nor disprove it from the other axioms, leaving a fundamental choice at the very foundation of modern mathematics—a rather unsettling thought for those who prefer absolute certainty.

• ...that the [Pythagorean Theorem](/Pythagorean_theorem), a cornerstone of geometry, actually generalizes far beyond squares, extending to any three similar shapes constructed on the three sides of a right-angled triangle? The elegance of this truth suggests a deeper, more universal principle at play than mere Euclidean areas.

• ...that the [orthocenter](/Orthocenter), the [circumcenter](/Circumcenter), the [centroid](/Centroid), and even the center of the [nine-point circle](/Nine-point_circle)—four distinct and significant points associated with any triangle—all lie perfectly on one single line, famously known as the [Euler line](/Euler_line)? A beautiful and unexpected alignment in the often chaotic world of triangles.

• ...that an arbitrary [quadrilateral](/Quadrilateral), regardless of its specific shape, will invariably [tessellate](/Tessellate), meaning it can completely tile a plane without any gaps or overlaps? A surprisingly generous property for such a simple polygon, demonstrating a fundamental capacity for pattern in even irregular forms.

• ...that it has not been definitively proven whether or not [every even integer greater than two can be expressed as the sum of two prime numbers](/Goldbach%27s_conjecture)? This seemingly simple statement, posed centuries ago, remains one of the most enduring and frustratingly elusive unsolved problems in all of number theory, a constant thorn in the side of mathematicians.

• ...that the [sum](/Summation) of the first *n* [odd numbers](/Odd_numbers) divided by the sum of the *next* *n* odd numbers is always precisely equal to one third? A curious and elegant numerical relationship, revealing hidden proportionalities within the sequence of odd integers.

• ...that *i* to the power of *i*, where *i* represents the [square root of -1](/Imaginary_unit)—a quantity so inherently imaginary—is, against all initial intuition, a perfectly real number? A stark reminder that the boundaries of reality in mathematics are often far more fluid and surprising than one might expect.

