Topics in mathematics

This section offers a fleeting glimpse into the vast intellectual domains that constitute mathematics. Consider it a table of contents for the universe's instruction manual, hastily compiled and still riddled with unknowns.

General

• [Mathematicians](/Mathematician): The flawed, brilliant, and often eccentric individuals who dare to plumb these depths.
• [History of mathematics](/History_of_mathematics): A chronological account of humanity's slow, often painful, crawl towards understanding.
• [Philosophy of mathematics](/Philosophy_of_mathematics): The endless, circular debates about what it all *means*.
• [Mathematical notation](/Mathematical_notation): The arcane symbols without which none of this would be intelligible.
• [Mathematical beauty](/Mathematical_beauty): The subjective aesthetic appeal some find in logical structures.
• [Mathematics education](/Mathematics_education): The Sisyphean task of attempting to impart this knowledge to the unwilling.
• [Glossary of mathematical symbols](/Glossary_of_mathematical_symbols): A necessary dictionary for the uninitiated, or those who simply forget.

Foundations

• [Foundations of mathematics](/Foundations_of_mathematics): The shaky ground upon which all other mathematical edifices are constructed.
• [Mathematical logic](/Mathematical_logic): The austere rules governing valid inference, often ignored in daily life.
• [Proof theory](/Proof_theory): The study of proofs, a meta-analysis of mathematical certainty.
• [Gödel's incompleteness theorems](/G%C3%B6del%27s_incompleteness_theorems): The uncomfortable truth that no sufficiently complex system can prove all its own truths.
• [Model theory](/Model_theory): How mathematical theories relate to their interpretations.
• [Recursion theory](/Recursion_theory): The study of computable functions and the limits of computation.
• [Set theory](/Set_theory): The fundamental language of collections, surprisingly controversial.
• [Naive set theory](/Naive_set_theory): The intuitive approach, prone to paradox.
• [Axiomatic set theory](/Axiomatic_set_theory): The attempt to build sets on firmer, albeit artificial, ground.
• [Category theory](/Category_theory): An abstract framework for relating different mathematical structures.
• [Topos theory](/Topos_theory): A highly abstract generalization of set theory and topology.

Number theory

• [Number theory](/Number_theory): The study of integers and their often enigmatic properties.
• [Algebraic number theory](/Algebraic_number_theory): Extending number theory to algebraic structures.
• [Analytic number theory](/Analytic_number_theory): Using tools from analysis to study numbers.
• [Arithmetic](/Arithmetic): The basic manipulations of numbers, surprisingly complex once you dig deeper.
• [Fundamental theorem of arithmetic](/Fundamental_theorem_of_arithmetic): The unique prime factorization, a bedrock truth.
• [Numbers](/Number): The very atoms of mathematics, from the concrete to the infinitely abstract.
• [Natural numbers](/Natural_number): The numbers you learn first, yet still full of mystery.
• [Prime numbers](/Prime_number): The indivisible building blocks, their distribution an enduring enigma.
• [Rational numbers](/Rational_number): Fractions, a step towards continuous quantities.
• [Algebraic numbers](/Algebraic_number): Roots of polynomial equations, a bridge between algebra and numbers.

Discrete mathematics

• [Discrete mathematics](/Discrete_mathematics): The mathematics of distinct, separable entities, often more relevant to computers than continuous reality.
• [Combinatorics](/Combinatorics): The art of counting arrangements, often leading to surprisingly large numbers.
• [Combinatorial geometry](/Combinatorial_geometry): The study of discrete geometric objects.
• [Coding theory](/Coding_theory): How to transmit information reliably, even when the universe conspires against you.
• [Combinatorial design](/Combinatorial_design): Constructing sets with specific intersection properties.
• [Enumerative combinatorics](/Enumerative_combinatorics): The systematic counting of discrete structures.
• [Combinatorial optimization](/Combinatorial_optimization): Finding the best solution among a finite set of possibilities.
• [Graph theory](/Graph_theory): The study of networks, representing relationships and connections.
• [Order theory](/Order_theory): The mathematical study of ordering relations.
• [Lattice theory](/Lattice_theory): The study of partially ordered sets with specific properties.
• [Digital Signal Processing](/Digital_Signal_Processing): Manipulating discrete signals, the language of modern media.
• [Theoretical computer science](/Theoretical_computer_science): The mathematical underpinnings of computation itself.
• [Computability theory](/Computability_theory_(computation)): What can and cannot be computed, a profound limit.
• [Complexity theory](/Computational_complexity_theory): How efficiently problems can be solved, or if they can be solved at all.

Algebra

• [Algebra](/Algebra): The language of symbols and rules, a powerful abstraction.
• [Elementary algebra](/Elementary_algebra): The gateway drug to mathematical abstraction.
• [Abstract algebra](/Abstract_algebra): The study of algebraic structures, stripped of specific numbers.
• [Group theory](/Group_theory): The mathematics of symmetry, fundamental to physics and chemistry.
• [Ring theory](/Ring_theory): Generalizing integers to structures with addition and multiplication.
• [Field theory](/Field_theory_(mathematics)): Structures where every non-zero element has a multiplicative inverse.
• [Commutative algebra](/Commutative_algebra): Rings where multiplication is commutative.
• [Geometric algebra](/Geometric_algebra): An algebraic framework for geometric operations.
• [Linear algebra](/Linear_algebra): The study of vectors, matrices, and linear transformations, essential for almost everything.
• [Matrix theory](/Matrix_(mathematics)): The properties and operations of rectangular arrays of numbers.
